Read in data

library(readr)
HairEyeColor <- read_csv("HairEyeColor.csv")

Hypothesis testing

one sample prop

eyecoltab<-table(HairEyeColor$eye)
prop.table(eyecoltab)
## 
##      Blue     Brown     Green     Hazel 
## 0.3631757 0.3716216 0.1081081 0.1570946
browncount<-eyecoltab["Brown"]
neye<-sum(eyecoltab)

prop.test(browncount,neye,p=0.5)
## 
##  1-sample proportions test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  browncount out of neye, null probability 0.5
## X-squared = 38.515, df = 1, p-value = 5.433e-10
## alternative hypothesis: true p is not equal to 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.3328182 0.4121162
## sample estimates:
##         p 
## 0.3716216

more than 2 levels

H 0 : p black=0.2 and p brown=0.2 and p blond=0.5 and p red=0.1

prop.table(table(HairEyeColor$hair))
## 
##     Black     Blond     Brown       Red 
## 0.1824324 0.2145270 0.4831081 0.1199324
# use chi.square test

chisq.test(table(HairEyeColor$hair),p=c(0.2,0.2,0.5,0.1))
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  table(HairEyeColor$hair)
## X-squared = 4.228, df = 3, p-value = 0.2379

2 category

chisq.test(table(HairEyeColor$eye,HairEyeColor$hair))
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table(HairEyeColor$eye, HairEyeColor$hair)
## X-squared = 138.29, df = 9, p-value < 2.2e-16

Continous

one sample

mean(iris$Sepal.Length)
## [1] 5.843333
t.test(iris$Sepal.Length)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  iris$Sepal.Length
## t = 86.425, df = 149, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  5.709732 5.976934
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  5.843333
qqnorm(iris$Sepal.Length)
qqline(iris$Sepal.Length)

# t-test depends on normal distribution of the data
# use shapiro can test the normal distributioon of data
shapiro.test(iris$Sepal.Length)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  iris$Sepal.Length
## W = 0.97609, p-value = 0.01018
# after log operation the data is normal distribution
logsl<-log10(iris$Sepal.Length)
shapiro.test(logsl)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  logsl
## W = 0.98253, p-value = 0.05388
t.test(logsl)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  logsl
## t = 152.27, df = 149, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.7524644 0.7722505
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
## 0.7623574
### compare with 6
t.test(iris$Sepal.Length, mu=6)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  iris$Sepal.Length
## t = -2.3172, df = 149, p-value = 0.02186
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 6
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  5.709732 5.976934
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  5.843333

two samples

# create 2 samples
versicolorsl<-iris$Sepal.Length[iris$Species=="versicolor"]
virginisl<-iris$Sepal.Length[iris$Species=="virginica"]

boxplot(versicolorsl)

boxplot(virginisl)

iris2pop<-iris[iris$Species!="setosa",]
boxplot(iris2pop$Sepal.Length~iris2pop$Species)

t.test(virginisl,versicolorsl, var.equal=T)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  virginisl and versicolorsl
## t = 5.6292, df = 98, p-value = 1.725e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4221484 0.8818516
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##     6.588     5.936
## equal

## unequal
t.test(virginisl,versicolorsl, var.equal=F)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  virginisl and versicolorsl
## t = 5.6292, df = 94.025, p-value = 1.866e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4220269 0.8819731
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##     6.588     5.936
## non-parameter test, applies to data that normal distribution failed
wilcox.test(virginisl,versicolorsl)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  virginisl and versicolorsl
## W = 1974, p-value = 5.869e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
shapiro.test(versicolorsl)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  versicolorsl
## W = 0.97784, p-value = 0.4647
shapiro.test(virginisl)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  virginisl
## W = 0.97118, p-value = 0.2583

tannin data

tannindata <- read.delim("C:/Users/YTan/Desktop/LearnR/Lesson_3_Building_model/tannin.txt")

ANOVA

gainsdata<-read.delim("growth.txt",header=T)
str(gainsdata)
## 'data.frame':    48 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ supplement: chr  "supergain" "supergain" "supergain" "supergain" ...
##  $ diet      : chr  "wheat" "wheat" "wheat" "wheat" ...
##  $ gain      : num  17.4 16.8 18.1 15.8 17.7 ...
gainsdata$supplement<-as.factor(gainsdata$supplement)

boxplot(gainsdata$gain~gainsdata$supplement)

gainsdata$supplement<-relevel(gainsdata$supplement,ref="control")

avmod<-lm(gain~supplement,data=gainsdata)
summary(avmod)

ANCOVA

Fruitdata<-read.delim("Fruit.txt",header=T)
str(Fruitdata)
## 'data.frame':    40 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ Root   : num  6.22 6.49 4.92 5.13 5.42 ...
##  $ Fruit  : num  59.8 61 14.7 19.3 34.2 ...
##  $ Grazing: chr  "Ungrazed" "Ungrazed" "Ungrazed" "Ungrazed" ...
Fruitdata$Grazing<-as.factor(Fruitdata$Grazing)

attach(Fruitdata)
plot(Root,Fruit)

boxplot(Fruit~Grazing)
library(lattice)

xyplot(Fruit~Root|Grazing)

fruitmodel1<-lm(Fruit~Root+Grazing+Root*Grazing,data=Fruitdata)
fruitmodel2<-lm(Fruit~Root+Grazing,data=Fruitdata)
